ChatGPT said:

Great question mate â€” this is the exact small detail that most people misunderstand.
Let me explain it fully clearly:

âœ… 1. data.json() returns a promise

Even though it gives you JSON, technically:

data.json()


returns a Promise, not the final object.

So both of these:

return data.json();


and

const result = await data.json();
return result;


are NOT the same thing, even though they look similar.

â­ CASE 1:
return data.json() â†’ returns a Promise

This returns a pending promise, not the final data.

This is what Suspense wants.

âœ” Good for client API with Suspense + use()
âœ” Good for streaming
âœ” Does NOT block the server
âœ” Does not wait for JSON parsing

â­ CASE 2:
const result = await data.json(); return result; â†’ returns actual JSON object

This returns the final resolved JSON, not a promise.

âœ” Good for normal server components
âœ” Good for normal API fetch
âŒ NOT good for Suspense streaming because Suspense requires a promise to suspend

ğŸ¯ So the difference is:
Code	What it returns	Good for
return data.json()	Promise	Client Components with use() / Suspense
const result = await data.json(); return result;	Actual JSON	Normal server rendering


